l%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fe3.365dm.com%2F25%2F04%2F1920x1080%2Fskynews-gaza-israel_6873550.jpg%3F20250402072841%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Fisrael-announces-military-operation-expanding-in-gaza-to-seize-large-areas-13340265%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Israel%20is%20beginning%20a%20major%20expansion%20of%20its%20military%20operation%20in%20Gaza%20and%20will%20seize%20large%20areas%20of%20the%20territory%2C%20the%20country's%20defence%20minister%20said.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A1461%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Fisrael-announces-military-operation-expanding-in-gaza-to-seize-large-areas-13340265%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews-sky-com.cdn.ampproject.org%2Fc%2Fs%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Famp%2Fisrael-announces-military-operation-expanding-in-gaza-to-seize-large-areas-13340265%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Famp%2Fisrael-announces-military-operation-expanding-in-gaza-to-seize-large-areas-13340265%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Only%20One%20US%20President%20Served%20More%20Than%202%20Terms.%20Here's%20Why%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cp%3EOnly%20one%20person%2C%20Franklin%20Delano%20Roosevelt%2C%20has%20ever%20served%20more%20than%20two%20terms%20as%20president%20of%20the%20United%20States.%20This%20is%20for%20two%20reasons.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFirst%2C%20prior%20to%20Roosevelt's%20election%20to%20a%20third%20term%20in%201940%20there%20was%20a%20longstanding%20American%20tradition%20that%20presidents%20not%20serve%20more%20than%20two%20terms.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20tradition%20was%20established%20by%20the%20decisions%20of%20early%20presidents%20such%20as%20George%20Washington%2C%20Thomas%20Jefferson%20and%20James%20Madison%20not%20to%20seek%20a%20third%20term.%20This%20tradition%20was%20later%20adopted%20by%20other%20presidents.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESecond%2C%20after%20Roosevelt%20died%20in%20office%20in%201945%20during%20his%20fourth%20term%2C%20Congress%20and%20the%20people%20of%20the%20United%20States%20decided%20to%20turn%20the%20long-standing%20tradition%20that%20presidents%20should%20not%20serve%20more%20than%20two%20terms%20into%20a%20part%20of%20constitutional%20law.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20was%20done%20through%20the%20passage%20and%20ratification%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fconstitution.congress.gov%2Fbrowse%2Fessay%2Famdt22-1%2FALDE_00001008%2F%5C%22%3E22nd%20Amendment%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20which%20became%20part%20of%20the%20US%20Constitution%20in%201951.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EIntent%20is%20clear%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20key%20provision%20of%20the%2022nd%20Amendment%20reads%20as%20follows%3A%20%E2%80%9CNo%20person%20shall%20be%20elected%20to%20the%20office%20of%20the%20President%20more%20than%20twice%2C%20and%20no%20person%20who%20has%20held%20the%20office%20of%20President%2C%20or%20acted%20as%20President%2C%20for%20more%20than%20two%20years%20of%20a%20term%20to%20which%20some%20other%20person%20was%20elected%20President%20shall%20be%20elected%20to%20the%20office%20of%20the%20President%20more%20than%20once.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20intent%20is%20clear.%20No%20one%20is%20supposed%20to%20serve%20more%20than%20two%20full%20terms%20as%20president.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20only%20way%20someone%20can%20serve%20more%20than%20two%20terms%20is%20if%20they%20served%20less%20than%20two%20years%20in%20a%20previous%20term%20in%20which%20they%20weren't%20elected%20president.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHere's%20an%20example%3A%20If%20a%20vice%20president%20becomes%20president%20during%20the%20final%20year%20of%20a%20term%20because%20the%20president%20died%2C%20that%20vice%20president%20could%20still%20run%20for%20two%20terms.%20But%20that%20exception%20is%20still%20meant%20to%20bar%20anyone%20from%20serving%20more%20than%20a%20total%20of%2010%20years%20as%20president.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20is%20worth%20understanding%20why%20the%20two-term%20tradition%20was%20considered%20so%20important%20that%20it%20was%20turned%20into%20constitutional%20law%20the%20first%20time%20it%20was%20violated.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EStarting%20the%20tradition%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECommentators%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fit.usembassy.gov%2Fthe-first-u-s-president-set-his-own-term-limit%2F%5C%22%3Eoften%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reaganlibrary.gov%2Fconstitutional-amendments-amendment-22-term-limits-presidency%5C%22%3Ecite%3C%2Fa%3E%20George%20Washington's%20decision%20not%20to%20seek%20a%20third%20term%20as%20president%20as%20establishing%20the%20two-term%20tradition.%20Political%20scientist%20and%20term%20limit%20scholar%20Michael%20Korzi%20gives%20a%20lot%20more%20credit%20to%20the%20nation's%20third%20president%2C%20Thomas%20Jefferson.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EJefferson%20was%20outspoken%20in%20favor%20of%20the%20two-term%20tradition.%20As%20Korzi%20notes%2C%20this%20was%2C%20in%20part%2C%20because%20%E2%80%9CJefferson%20saw%20little%20distinction%20between%20a%20long-serving%20executive%20in%20an%20elective%20position%20and%20a%20hereditary%20monarch.%E2%80%9D%20In%20other%20words%2C%20a%20president%20without%20term%20limits%20is%20too%20much%20like%20a%20king.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EJefferson%20saw%20a%20president%20who%20was%20willing%20to%20break%20the%20two-term%20tradition%20as%20power-hungry%2C%20and%20he%20hoped%20that%20the%20American%20people%20would%20not%20elect%20such%20a%20president.%20This%20led%20him%20to%20write%20in%20his%20autobiography%20in%201821%20that%20%E2%80%9Cshould%20a%20President%20consent%20to%20be%20a%20candidate%20for%20a%203d.%20election%2C%20I%20trust%20he%20would%20be%20rejected%20on%20this%20demonstration%20of%20ambitious%20views.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EJefferson%20also%20worried%20that%20without%20term%20limits%2C%20presidents%20would%20stay%20in%20office%20too%20long%20into%20their%20old%20age%20and%20after%20they%20had%20lost%20their%20ability%20to%20govern%20effectively.%20This%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fscholarship.law.umn.edu%2Fcgi%2Fviewcontent.cgi%3Farticle%3D1908%26context%3Dmlr%5C%22%3Eled%20him%20to%20write%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20without%20term%20limits%2C%20there%20was%20a%20danger%20that%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20indulgence%20and%20attachments%20of%20the%20people%20will%20keep%20a%20man%20in%20the%20chair%20after%20he%20becomes%20a%20dotard.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESubsequently%2C%20presidents%20tended%20to%20abide%20by%20the%20two-term%20tradition.%20And%20in%20the%20few%20cases%20where%20presidents%20decided%20to%20seek%20a%20third%20term%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2025%2F03%2F31%2Fus%2Fpolitics%2Ftrump-presidential-term-limits.html%5C%22%3Etheir%20own%20parties%3C%2Fa%3E%20would%20not%20give%20them%20the%20nomination.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThat%20remained%20true%20until%20Roosevelt%20ran%20for%2C%20and%20won%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.fdrlibrary.org%2Ffdr-presidency%5C%22%3Eboth%20a%20third%20and%20a%20fourth%20term%3C%2Fa%3E%20as%20president%20during%20World%20War%20II.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%2022nd%20Amendment%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERoosevelt's%20violation%20of%20the%20two-term%20tradition%20prompted%20Congress%20and%20the%20states%20to%20turn%20the%20tradition%20into%20a%20formal%20matter%20of%20constitutional%20law.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20major%20concern%20motivating%20the%20amendment%20was%20the%20same%20one%20that%20motivated%20Jefferson%3A%20to%20prevent%20a%20president%20from%20becoming%20a%20king.%20Multiple%20members%20of%20Congress%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbclawreview.bc.edu%2Farticles%2F590%2Ffiles%2F63ad8d8b8d4c2.pdf%5C%22%3Eidentified%20the%20same%20concern%3C%2Fa%3E%20during%20congressional%20sessions%20in%20the%201940s.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESen.%20Chapman%20Revercomb%20from%20West%20Virginia%20stated%20that%20power%20given%20to%20a%20president%20without%20term%20limits%20%E2%80%9Cwould%20be%20a%20definite%20step%20in%20the%20direction%20of%20autocracy%2C%20regardless%20of%20the%20name%20given%20the%20office%2C%20whether%20it%20be%20president%2C%20king%2C%20dictator%2C%20emperor%2C%20or%20whatever%20title%20the%20office%20may%20carry.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESimilarly%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbioguide.congress.gov%2Fsearch%2Fbio%2FM000374%5C%22%3ERep.%20Edward%20McCowen%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20Ohio%20said%20that%20the%2022nd%20Amendment%20would%20be%20%E2%80%9Ca%20great%20step%20toward%20preventing%20a%20dictatorship%20or%20some%20totalitarian%20form%20of%20government%20from%20arising.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnd%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbioguide.congress.gov%2Fsearch%2Fbio%2FJ000096%5C%22%3ERep.%20John%20Jennings%20Jr.%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20Tennessee%20stated%20that%20only%20by%20adoption%20of%20the%2022nd%20Amendment%20%E2%80%9Ccan%20the%20people%20be%20assured%20that%20we%20shall%20never%20have%20a%20dictator%20in%20this%20land.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fconstitutioncenter.org%2Fblog%2Fhow-the-22nd-amendment-came-into-existence%5C%22%3ECongress%20passed%20the%2022nd%20Amendment%3C%2Fa%3E%20on%20March%2021%2C%201947.%20It%20took%20less%20than%20four%20years%20for%20the%20necessary%20three-fourths%20of%20the%20states%20to%20ratify%20the%20amendment%2C%20which%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Ftopic%2FTwenty-second-Amendment%5C%22%3Ebecame%20law%20on%20Feb.%2027%2C%201951%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cfigure%3E%5Cn%3Cfigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ffigure%3E%5Cn%3Cfigure%3E%5Cn%3Cfigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ffigure%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3ETyrants%20and%20term%20limit%20violations%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%201980s%2C%20political%20scientist%20Juan%20Linz%20identified%20that%20presidential%20systems%20are%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fjustice-everywhere.org%2Fdemocracy%2Fthe-united-states-perils-of-presidentialism%2F%5C%22%3Eless%20stable%3C%2Fa%3E%20than%20other%20forms%20of%20democracy%2C%20such%20as%20parliamentary%20systems.%20The%20difference%20seems%20to%20be%20that%20presidential%20systems%20concentrate%20more%20power%20in%20the%20hands%20of%20a%20single%20person%2C%20the%20president.%20This%20makes%20it%20easier%20to%20remove%20the%20checks%20and%20balances%20that%20democracies%20depend%20on.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAs%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmuse.jhu.edu%2Farticle%2F607612%5C%22%3Escholars%20have%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpapers.ssrn.com%2Fsol3%2Fpapers.cfm%3Fabstract_id%3D3670337%5C%22%3Enoted%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20violation%20of%20presidential%20term%20limits%20and%20other%20methods%20of%20increasing%20executive%20power%20are%20a%20common%20form%20of%20democratic%20backsliding%20%E2%80%93%20state-led%20debilitation%20or%20elimination%20of%20the%20political%20institutions%20that%20sustain%20a%20democracy.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELaw%20professor%20Mila%20Versteeg%20and%20her%20colleagues%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcolumbialawreview.org%2Fcontent%2Fthe-law-and-politics-of-presidential-term-limit-evasion%2F%5C%22%3Ehave%20shown%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20in%20recent%20years%20presidents%20around%20the%20globe%20have%20used%20various%20tactics%20to%20try%20to%20violate%20presidential%20term%20limits.%20These%20tactics%20include%20trying%20to%20amend%20their%20country's%20constitution%2C%20trying%20to%20get%20the%20courts%20to%20reinterpret%20the%20constitution%2C%20finding%20a%20replacement%20leader%20who%20the%20former%20president%20can%20control%20once%20out%20of%20office%20and%20attempting%20to%20delay%20elections.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThey%20note%20that%20most%20of%20the%20time%20when%20a%20president's%20attempt%20to%20violate%20term%20limits%20fails%20it%20is%20%E2%80%9Cbecause%20the%20attempt%20encountered%20widespread%20popular%20resistance.%E2%80%9D%20They%20conclude%20that%20this%20finding%20implies%20that%20%E2%80%9Cbroad%20resistance%20movements%E2%80%9D%20may%2